WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:04.680
Welcome everyone, thanks for sticking with us here in this Drugs Not Bugs

00:00:04.680 --> 00:00:12.200
section. So yeah, I recently turned 40. Yeah, this is the age where people with

00:00:12.200 --> 00:00:18.160
experience say things like, I tweaked my back getting out of the car or, you know,

00:00:18.160 --> 00:00:23.160
I can't eat that, it has too much cholesterol. So now that I've joined this

00:00:23.160 --> 00:00:28.879
lovely group, I decided I should set a meeting with my doctor. When I showed up

00:00:28.879 --> 00:00:32.840
for that meeting, I learned something new about myself. So I have something

00:00:32.840 --> 00:00:37.580
called white coat syndrome and some of you might be familiar with that. Now what

00:00:37.580 --> 00:00:42.000
that means for me is, the longer I think about my blood pressure, the higher it

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:49.400
goes. So talking with some friends the next day about this situation with my

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:54.759
blood pressure, one insisted, hey, come to the gym with me, I'll pick you up at 5

00:00:54.759 --> 00:01:00.119
a.m. Really casual like that, like people wake up at 5 a.m. to work out. So I have

00:01:00.119 --> 00:01:06.839
to do something, so I agree. 5 a.m. comes quickly and I've never worked out at a

00:01:06.839 --> 00:01:12.040
gym in my life, lifted weights, so I didn't quite know what to expect and my

00:01:12.040 --> 00:01:16.680
experience was something like this.

00:01:18.839 --> 00:01:24.360
So believe it or not, when I think back about this now, it actually is a

00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:29.919
close parallel to my open-source journey. So I found that I needed to

00:01:29.919 --> 00:01:35.919
make a change. I knew that not making a change could be detrimental, but it was

00:01:35.919 --> 00:01:39.879
really scary walking into something like this, thinking how I could actually

00:01:39.879 --> 00:01:44.879
contribute here. So I'd like to take you through that open-source journey and

00:01:44.879 --> 00:01:48.480
hopefully it helps some of you along the way. Now when I think about this

00:01:48.480 --> 00:01:54.680
open-source journey, I dump it into roughly, well, exactly three buckets.

00:01:54.680 --> 00:01:59.199
Organizations thinking about using open-source, organizations that are

00:01:59.199 --> 00:02:03.080
currently implementing open-source, and then the last bucket of kind of been

00:02:03.080 --> 00:02:09.800
there, done that, have the t-shirt, so to speak. You might be saying, okay, well why

00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:13.399
are we talking about organizations? I'm just a happy bucket that likes to

00:02:13.399 --> 00:02:19.080
program. But organizations are simply made up of people, they're made up of you

00:02:19.080 --> 00:02:24.199
all, and I want to challenge everyone here or invite you to think about this

00:02:24.199 --> 00:02:29.559
from an organization perspective as we talk about this. How can adopting

00:02:29.559 --> 00:02:35.440
open-source help your company improve, not just yourself? And I want you all to

00:02:35.440 --> 00:02:41.080
believe that you have the ability to drive open-source change within your

00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:47.919
organization. So for you as a driver of change, thinking about how to get your

00:02:47.919 --> 00:02:54.399
organization to use open-source, you're gonna run into some questions. It might

00:02:54.399 --> 00:02:58.320
be something like, hey, I love R, I love Python, but how do I gain support so I

00:02:58.320 --> 00:03:04.639
can use it for my everyday work? You know, should we have an open-source

00:03:04.639 --> 00:03:08.440
group dedicated to this within our organization? And if so, how do you

00:03:08.479 --> 00:03:14.520
actually build one? And then where to even start? There's so many ways to go

00:03:14.520 --> 00:03:21.039
with this, and as corny as it is, it's really just dive in, you know. So and

00:03:21.039 --> 00:03:26.279
hopefully my story and our story really will help you to avoid some of those

00:03:26.279 --> 00:03:33.839
rocks around the edges. So a story of what we did here, right? So we knew we

00:03:33.839 --> 00:03:40.960
needed to show value. We knew that if we could show value, we could build

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:47.960
credibility by showing value. And then we knew we needed more people than what we

00:03:47.960 --> 00:03:56.039
had to achieve our goals. And the way we really did this was, to Eric's point,

00:03:56.039 --> 00:04:00.600
like, interactivity is really powerful here, right? And something new and wild.

00:04:00.600 --> 00:04:04.679
And if you're able to take that, take quick wins. And for us, a lot of that was

00:04:04.679 --> 00:04:09.399
taking things, just take something out of Excel, dump it in Shiny. Seems kind of

00:04:09.399 --> 00:04:15.479
silly, but it's a way to quickly show some value. And don't start from scratch,

00:04:15.479 --> 00:04:18.440
like steel code. That's the great thing about open source when you join, right?

00:04:18.440 --> 00:04:22.160
So there's Shiny galleries out there. I believe for the example I'm about to

00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:27.279
show, it was from BS4Dash. So if David's out there, thank you. You can go to these

00:04:27.279 --> 00:04:31.200
repositories, grab examples, copy, paste, and start just tweaking and changing

00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:39.079
things. All right. So an example. We had an old Excel process where we identified

00:04:39.079 --> 00:04:43.799
adverse events, and it simply just exceeded some threshold, or maybe you were

00:04:43.799 --> 00:04:46.600
comparing treatments and you wanted to look at some differential between

00:04:46.600 --> 00:04:52.440
treatments. So the process would be, open your output, copy all of that, open Excel,

00:04:52.559 --> 00:04:58.160
dump it in there, and now you could start slicing and dicing your data. We just put

00:04:58.160 --> 00:05:03.040
that in Shiny. It wasn't really a radical change. It was just now that instead of

00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:08.279
opening an output in Excel, you open your Shiny app, browse for files, select them,

00:05:08.279 --> 00:05:14.200
load them up, slice and dice your data. But what we found was it's easier to use,

00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:20.040
and it reduced a lot of that copy-paste error, or accidentally modifying some part

00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:24.200
of the Excel file that you didn't intend to modify, and it really just led to

00:05:24.200 --> 00:05:29.000
faster, higher-quality results that translated to roughly a quarter million

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:34.399
dollars a year. Now, that's more money than I make in a year, so I was thinking,

00:05:34.399 --> 00:05:37.600
hey, we're doing pretty good here, right, for a couple weeks of work.

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:42.760
So we're able to show quick value and maybe pose that question to your

00:05:42.760 --> 00:05:46.760
leadership, right? Well, what if you had two people working on this full-time?

00:05:46.760 --> 00:05:50.000
What if you had three? And really, the point is, you know,

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:56.839
what can you achieve here if you invest resources here? All right, great.

00:05:56.839 --> 00:06:03.160
So you've got a team dedicated on delivering value using open-source tools.

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:06.640
When you move into that next bucket, you might start thinking about questions

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:11.480
of, how do we expand this more broadly? How could maybe we have a department

00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:18.640
to begin using open-source tools? And when you move into this bucket,

00:06:18.640 --> 00:06:22.679
especially when thinking about terms of regulatory deliverables,

00:06:22.679 --> 00:06:27.600
it changes from not what you're doing, but it's really how you do it, right?

00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:32.880
So you could build a house, but when you step back and you look at this house,

00:06:32.880 --> 00:06:35.959
if it's looking something like this, you're probably not going to want to live

00:06:35.959 --> 00:06:42.600
in that house. So the questions you really run into in this bucket are,

00:06:42.600 --> 00:06:48.679
you know, are your results reproducible? Is the software that you're using trusted?

00:06:48.679 --> 00:06:52.959
And we have to remember also to Eric's point, like, we already have a house.

00:06:52.959 --> 00:06:56.040
Like, why are we changing? Is this actually getting treatments

00:06:56.040 --> 00:07:00.959
to patients faster? And it's really easy to lose that when you get in the weeds

00:07:00.959 --> 00:07:07.720
of this stuff, so. All right, so how did we build our house?

00:07:07.720 --> 00:07:12.640
If you've never built a house before, and I had not, one thing that's great

00:07:12.640 --> 00:07:17.359
to have is a general contractor, right? So a general contractor understands you

00:07:17.359 --> 00:07:21.279
need a plumber, you need an electrician, you're going to need some painters.

00:07:21.279 --> 00:07:24.720
They also understand the order you're going to need those things,

00:07:24.720 --> 00:07:29.000
and they speak the language of those trades. They can effectively communicate

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:35.040
across these roles to get things done as needed. And I'd like to say that the

00:07:35.040 --> 00:07:41.760
modernization of statistical analytics plays that role of the general contractor.

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:44.760
They're not going to come build your house for you, but they are going to help you

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:48.959
understand who needs to be there while you're building your house,

00:07:48.959 --> 00:07:55.959
and also how to communicate effectively to those groups. All right, so again,

00:07:55.959 --> 00:07:58.399
general contractors aren't plumbers. They're not electricians.

00:07:58.399 --> 00:08:02.239
They're not going to build your house. But they do know a lot of plumbers

00:08:02.239 --> 00:08:05.799
and electricians, and they know which ones are good and which ones aren't.

00:08:05.799 --> 00:08:10.440
And that's kind of what we think about with selecting software, right?

00:08:10.440 --> 00:08:15.399
So the R Validation Hub, another working group within the R Consortium,

00:08:15.399 --> 00:08:20.480
is here to help you along the way. They're really the go-to to help guide you

00:08:20.480 --> 00:08:23.440
in picking the correct software, and most importantly,

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:28.279
documenting that correctly. All right, so we built the house.

00:08:28.279 --> 00:08:32.200
Let's move in, right? There's still that last piece of inspection,

00:08:32.200 --> 00:08:36.440
and this is really where regulatory comes in. And the work Eric's already touched

00:08:36.440 --> 00:08:40.799
on here with another working group within R Consortium, the Submissions Group,

00:08:40.799 --> 00:08:47.400
has many examples there to help you safely and correctly document and deliver

00:08:47.400 --> 00:08:53.719
to regulatory agencies while using open source. And I mean, this isn't everything,

00:08:53.719 --> 00:08:59.159
but this is essentially how we built our house. We leaned on the open source community.

00:08:59.159 --> 00:09:03.640
We joined open source initiatives, and we really learned from the industry

00:09:03.640 --> 00:09:10.239
as we ran into challenges. And again, let's not forget why we built this house, right?

00:09:10.239 --> 00:09:17.359
Again, you had a house in the first place. So we need to get treatment to patients faster.

00:09:17.960 --> 00:09:22.599
So regardless of open source, standards is always a good way to do this, right?

00:09:22.599 --> 00:09:28.400
And the Pharmaverse is a group of people working to curate packages specific to our industry.

00:09:28.400 --> 00:09:33.919
The aim really, in my view, and others, I believe, is standardizing the set of packages

00:09:33.919 --> 00:09:39.919
that regulatory reviewers are seeing. If each time a reviewer pops open the trial

00:09:39.919 --> 00:09:44.159
that they're working towards, and they see a new set of packages,

00:09:44.159 --> 00:09:47.599
maybe proprietary packages, and they have to spend time sorting out,

00:09:47.599 --> 00:09:50.760
hey, do I trust this? What are they doing? How do they program this?

00:09:50.760 --> 00:09:56.679
It's the opposite of speeding things up, right? We're going to be slowing things down even further.

00:09:56.679 --> 00:10:00.880
So we really want to see people using a standard set.

00:10:00.880 --> 00:10:04.159
And as a reviewer gets one package for the first time that's new,

00:10:04.159 --> 00:10:08.719
well, if the next one they get is the same one, they slowly hopefully build that trust,

00:10:08.719 --> 00:10:10.159
and it will help speed things along.

00:10:13.559 --> 00:10:18.640
Now, if we move past packages, and for those that know the Cardinal package already,

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:22.239
I made this logo up because they didn't have one, so this isn't the actual logo.

00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:29.320
You know, if we can think less about how do the results look on a page,

00:10:29.320 --> 00:10:33.159
the layout of those results, and focus more on is it accurate?

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:37.239
This allows things like Cardinal to be built,

00:10:37.239 --> 00:10:40.719
where this is just a package of table generating functions, right?

00:10:40.719 --> 00:10:43.400
Plug your data in, boom, you get your results.

00:10:43.400 --> 00:10:46.479
And if you don't care that this number is here instead of here,

00:10:46.479 --> 00:10:50.159
we can really begin to move past that, have some sort of industry standards

00:10:50.159 --> 00:10:52.000
to really begin to speed things up here.

00:10:54.679 --> 00:10:57.039
And then, again, interactivity.

00:10:57.039 --> 00:11:00.599
So there's interactive frameworks like Rhino and Teal out there

00:11:00.599 --> 00:11:05.280
that provide standard ways for you to give interactivity to your stakeholders.

00:11:06.359 --> 00:11:08.960
This allows them to answer questions in real time,

00:11:08.960 --> 00:11:11.640
and more quickly understand and summarize their findings.

00:11:11.640 --> 00:11:16.320
So I'd say these are the three big items, in my view, of really speeding things up.

00:11:20.799 --> 00:11:22.960
All right, so you've built your open source team.

00:11:22.960 --> 00:11:26.039
You've expanded the scope of use to maybe a department.

00:11:27.039 --> 00:11:30.400
You might be feeling, hey, you know, we've done it.

00:11:30.400 --> 00:11:33.520
We've been there, done that, have the T-shirt, so to speak.

00:11:34.840 --> 00:11:38.880
But when I talk to organizations that I feel like fall in this bucket,

00:11:38.880 --> 00:11:42.320
surprisingly, they don't think they've been there, done that, have the T-shirt.

00:11:43.840 --> 00:11:46.479
And they know that there's just so much left to do.

00:11:47.840 --> 00:11:52.400
And like with what Mark was talking about earlier, people is a big part of that.

00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:55.280
You can build your house, but if no one's moving into it,

00:11:55.280 --> 00:11:57.919
it doesn't matter how great it is or what the cool features are.

00:11:58.479 --> 00:12:03.200
And in the other respect, as far as, again, Eric's talk,

00:12:03.200 --> 00:12:04.520
there's always new technology.

00:12:04.520 --> 00:12:09.239
So those roadblocks that we had, new technology we see with WebAssembly comes out,

00:12:09.239 --> 00:12:12.000
and all of a sudden, hey, we see a whole better,

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:16.119
easier way to actually tackle a roadblock that's a major roadblock.

00:12:16.919 --> 00:12:20.640
So staying up with new technology is something we're always going to need to do.

00:12:20.640 --> 00:12:25.440
All right.

00:12:25.440 --> 00:12:29.039
So if you're using R now as part of this process,

00:12:29.840 --> 00:12:32.880
you really need to think about, okay, well, how do we keep this sustainable?

00:12:34.320 --> 00:12:38.640
And one way to just kind of get started is you've got a package pipeline now.

00:12:38.640 --> 00:12:39.760
Pick a package, right?

00:12:39.760 --> 00:12:41.359
Pick a package and join in.

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:44.960
And this is the first package I ever contributed to.

00:12:44.960 --> 00:12:48.719
So when we were building our house, I asked the question,

00:12:48.719 --> 00:12:50.559
all right, how are we addressing logging in R?

00:12:50.559 --> 00:12:53.599
Seems kind of like just a side thing you don't really think about.

00:12:55.039 --> 00:12:55.840
No one really knew.

00:12:55.840 --> 00:12:59.599
So I began looking, and I ran across the Farmiverse.

00:12:59.599 --> 00:13:01.359
There was a group of people working on this.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:05.840
I contacted them, reached out, and joined the group.

00:13:05.840 --> 00:13:09.760
And ever since then, actually, this is still my favorite package to work on, which is funny.

00:13:11.039 --> 00:13:15.599
The team is just awesome and just a great experience.

00:13:15.599 --> 00:13:19.039
So I encourage you to also just pick a package and hop in.

00:13:21.359 --> 00:13:21.919
All right.

00:13:21.919 --> 00:13:27.599
So later today, there is actually a Strengthening the R Ecosystem session

00:13:27.599 --> 00:13:29.359
that I would encourage you to attend.

00:13:29.359 --> 00:13:30.960
One of those talks is from Heather Turner.

00:13:31.760 --> 00:13:34.880
She'll actually be telling you exactly how to contribute to the R project.

00:13:35.440 --> 00:13:36.400
This one seems scary.

00:13:36.400 --> 00:13:39.280
I still haven't done this, but I'm going to dip my toes in the water,

00:13:39.280 --> 00:13:42.080
and I would encourage you to think of the same thing, right?

00:13:42.080 --> 00:13:44.559
How do we now contribute to core base R things?

00:13:46.559 --> 00:13:50.239
And we've heard R Consortium come up quite a bit, right?

00:13:50.239 --> 00:13:51.679
And there's a reason for that.

00:13:51.679 --> 00:13:56.080
So basically, the R Consortium is supporting social and infrastructure projects.

00:13:57.280 --> 00:14:01.679
They're really trying to spread the use of R and provide money through grants

00:14:01.679 --> 00:14:06.239
to ensure that R remains stable and R remains relevant.

00:14:06.239 --> 00:14:11.039
So joining this actually helps us as an industry

00:14:11.039 --> 00:14:14.080
make sure we're setting ourselves up for long-term success.

00:14:16.559 --> 00:14:17.039
All right.

00:14:17.039 --> 00:14:18.640
Sure, we can sustain, right?

00:14:18.640 --> 00:14:21.039
But also, we would like to grow R.

00:14:22.719 --> 00:14:26.000
And one way I encourage you to do that is things like this.

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:28.559
Share your story.

00:14:28.559 --> 00:14:31.679
It might not feel unique, but it is, and it will connect with someone.

00:14:33.599 --> 00:14:35.919
If you'd like something a little more informal,

00:14:35.919 --> 00:14:38.960
Rachel Dempsey runs a data science hangout every single week,

00:14:38.960 --> 00:14:41.119
and you can share your story there.

00:14:41.119 --> 00:14:43.280
And if you say, hey, I just don't want to talk to people,

00:14:43.840 --> 00:14:45.119
there's blogs and things like that.

00:14:45.919 --> 00:14:48.960
You can also still share your story.

00:14:51.760 --> 00:14:52.159
All right.

00:14:52.159 --> 00:14:53.679
And as you're building that house,

00:14:54.239 --> 00:14:57.200
you're probably going to run into things where you see gaps.

00:14:57.200 --> 00:14:59.599
You don't see really someone in the industry working on it.

00:14:59.599 --> 00:15:00.640
Maybe it's hard to find.

00:15:02.159 --> 00:15:05.280
And in that case, I would encourage that you organize and lead.

00:15:05.280 --> 00:15:08.880
And you can do that through R Consortium as well, starting working groups.

00:15:09.840 --> 00:15:12.719
There's one I haven't spoken about, which is FUSE,

00:15:12.719 --> 00:15:16.080
which has been helping the pharma industry for many years now.

00:15:16.080 --> 00:15:20.159
They also have a working group covering open source.

00:15:20.159 --> 00:15:23.440
And there's a project request form that you can just put in and say,

00:15:23.440 --> 00:15:25.280
hey, I found a new gap.

00:15:25.280 --> 00:15:27.840
I think this is something we need to come together as an industry.

00:15:29.039 --> 00:15:31.919
And you can request a new working group project.

00:15:32.799 --> 00:15:34.880
I do have supplemental information with all this stuff,

00:15:34.880 --> 00:15:37.200
so I'll share that at the end as well.

00:15:40.400 --> 00:15:40.799
All right.

00:15:41.599 --> 00:15:47.760
So now for the end of my story around my blood pressure and this crazy gym.

00:15:48.400 --> 00:15:52.000
So I'm still waking up at 5 a.m. and going to the gym.

00:15:52.719 --> 00:15:56.400
My blood pressure is way down, and I'm in great health now.

00:15:57.919 --> 00:16:00.400
And the analogy to me seems stronger than ever,

00:16:00.400 --> 00:16:03.359
that you really need to change to survive and thrive.

00:16:04.559 --> 00:16:07.840
So I hope you find a reason to make a change,

00:16:08.719 --> 00:16:15.840
to just dive in, to become a leader in moving your organization to open source.

00:16:16.880 --> 00:16:19.440
And remembering that there's other people to help you along the way.

00:16:20.559 --> 00:16:24.640
And I hope you remember to also remain a good steward of open source

00:16:24.640 --> 00:16:27.520
and help to maintain the stability and success

00:16:28.640 --> 00:16:33.679
as our industry adopts open source to get treatments to patients in time.

00:16:33.679 --> 00:16:41.039
Thank you.

00:16:42.719 --> 00:16:43.280
Thank you, Nick.

00:16:44.559 --> 00:16:48.559
As a fellow 40-plus person with hypertension, appreciate the talk.

00:16:50.799 --> 00:16:51.520
Very interesting.

00:16:51.520 --> 00:16:59.679
Can you give us some more story on that first contribution you did to the package, to LogRx?

00:16:59.679 --> 00:17:00.479
To LogRx?

00:17:01.280 --> 00:17:01.599
Yeah.

00:17:02.559 --> 00:17:05.920
Again, we were building our house, and logging came up,

00:17:05.920 --> 00:17:08.800
and I wasn't quite sure what we were going to do.

00:17:08.800 --> 00:17:13.119
So when I found the group, I reached out to just try to understand what they're doing

00:17:13.119 --> 00:17:15.680
and help them understand where I was coming from.

00:17:16.959 --> 00:17:21.520
From those conversations, it became really clear we could collaborate, right?

00:17:21.520 --> 00:17:22.719
They were very welcoming.

00:17:22.719 --> 00:17:25.040
It was kind of scary because it was the first time.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:27.760
Lovely group of people, extremely welcoming.

00:17:27.760 --> 00:17:31.680
And any package I've ever worked on ever since then, it's been the exact same experience.

00:17:31.680 --> 00:17:36.239
So we just talked through, planned some sprints just like you would for anything,

00:17:36.239 --> 00:17:38.319
worked on things, said, hey, what do you need?

00:17:38.319 --> 00:17:39.760
Hey, what do I need?

00:17:39.760 --> 00:17:42.560
Planned it out and just got to work.

00:17:42.560 --> 00:17:46.560
And I think since then, we probably get together once a year,

00:17:46.560 --> 00:17:48.319
and we just work through a sprint cycle.

00:17:48.319 --> 00:17:50.000
So it's been a great experience.

00:17:52.640 --> 00:17:53.920
Thank you again, Nick.

00:17:53.920 --> 00:17:54.800
I really appreciate it.

00:17:57.760 --> 00:17:58.400
